Task: Create DiscoursePrompt component

Summary:
Implemented a visually distinct discourse prompt component for "Think About It" questions. The component supports an optional expandable area for student responses with smooth animations and full accessibility support.

Files Created:
- components/textbook/DiscoursePrompt.tsx (71 lines)
- __tests__/components/textbook/DiscoursePrompt.test.tsx (238 lines)

Files Modified:
- components/textbook/index.ts (added DiscoursePrompt export)

Implementation Details:
- Props: prompt (required), title (optional, default: 'Think About It'), expandableArea (optional)
- State: useState tracks expanded/collapsed state for expandable content
- Visual: Accent color scheme (border-accent/30, bg-accent/5), MessageSquare icon, rounded container
- Typography: font-display (Lora) for title, proper line heights for prompt
- Expandable: Toggle button with ChevronDown/ChevronUp icon, smooth animation on expand/collapse
- Animation: Tailwind animate-in (fade-in, slide-in-from-top-2, duration-200)
- Accessibility: aria-expanded, aria-controls, proper heading structure (h4), keyboard accessible button
- Client Component: Uses 'use client' directive for state management

Test Coverage (21 tests):
- Basic rendering (prompt text, default title, custom title)
- Expandable area (renders when provided, not when absent, collapsed by default, expands/collapses on click, button text updates)
- Visual styling (distinct appearance, color scheme, spacing)
- Icon (renders MessageSquare icon)
- Accessibility (heading structure, button accessible, aria attributes, aria-expanded updates)
- Edge cases (empty prompt, long prompt, multiline prompt, complex expandable content)

All tests passing, lint passing, typecheck passing.

Why:
DiscoursePrompt provides a dedicated, visually distinct space for reflection questions and discussion prompts. The expandable area allows students to write and submit their responses without cluttering the main content area. The distinctive styling helps students identify these prompts as opportunities for deeper engagement with the material, supporting the instructional model's emphasis on discourse and reflection.
